\section{Syntax}\label{sec:syntax}

\subsection{Surface Syntax} \label{sec:syntax:surface}

The verifier takes as input programs written in the \emph{surface} syntax
whose grammar is summarized in Figure~\ref{fig:surface-syntax}.
%
The terms $|t|$ of the surface language include the usual
elements of Verse:
variables $|x|$,
integer constants $|k|$,
branches $|myite t_1 t_2 t_3|$,
tuples $|tup (t_1,xdots,t_n)|$,
existential bindings $|def x t|$,
unification equations $|t_1 = t_2|$,
sequences $|t_1 ; t_2|$,
choices $|t_1 choice t_2|$, $|one t|$ and $|all t|$ terms.
%
There are two kinds of function applications ---
$|t_1^[t_2]|$ which indicates the call is allowed to |fail|, and
$|t_1^(t_2)|$ which indicates the call must not |fail|.
%
Finally, we have two kinds of function definitions.
%
The first kind elides an explicit type for the function's output,
while the second provides one.
%
In either case the function definition is annotated with a type
for the input binder $|x:t|$ and an effect $|tup (fx)|$ which denotes
if the function |succeedKW| (which is the default, if an annotation is elided),
or |decideKW|.


\subsection{Core Syntax} \label{sec:syntax:core}

% \figureSyntax

The verifier's language is an extension of Core Verse \cite{fullversepaper}
with a few constructs that record the verification goals and the assumptions under which
they must be proved.
%
These extensions are summarized in Figure~\ref{fig:verifier-syntax}.
%
The |myite e_1 e_2 e_3| construct makes it easier to use
the information established by the branch (|e_1|) in the |then|
expression |e_2|.
%
The |assume e| construct records an \emph{assumption} that
the evaluation of |e| always produces a value \ie does not
get stuck or |fail|.
%
Dually, the |succeed e| construct (perhaps better named |succeeds|)
denotes an \emph{obligation} that the evaluation of |e| always
produces a value \ie does not get stuck or fail.
%
The |decide e| construct denotes an \emph{obligation} that
the evaluation of |e| does not get \emph{stuck} \ie either
produces values or fails.
